According to the clarifications in the comment section, I would do it like below. I assume, that you have an array with data objects. This array is displayed in its entirety when there are no filters in the `filters` array. If there are any filters in it, it will only display the filtered items. There is a computed property which returns always the relevant set of items.

I&#39;ve added two computed properties which return possible attribute values. So, if there is an `animalType` property in the object, every possible value of this `animalType` is retrieved from the data. This is done with each property for all the data items. Boolean values are filtered out.

When using boolean values, not the value is important but the key. So, similarly to every other property, each key (instead of their values) is returned for booleans.

Those two arrays are then used to filter the effective data. The filtering is still by value (comparison with `===`). So, if you are having an object as an attribute value, this won&#39;t work (except it has the same object reference..)

Here is also a [CodePen](https://codepen.io/ssc-hrep3/pen/zYOLpQb) to try it out.

